      "text": "So it looks like instead of manufacturing everything in-house using copper/aluminum, they may have: bought more ready-made components/products from vendors and directly sold them. That shifts the cost from: “Raw material consumed” → to → “Stock-in-trade purchases”. Still, your observation is valid because copper/aluminum prices were high, and inventory wasn’t large enough to fully explain this shift. Worth tracking: what exactly they traded, whether outsourcing has increased, and if this becomes a permanent trend.",
